fr:title.text: Subobject classifiers are equivalently representations of the subobject functor

fr:frontmatter.fr:title: Subobject classifiers are equivalently representations of the subobject functor

fr:mainmatter.fr:p: Let C be finitely complete and locally small. Then C has a subobject classifier if and only if the subobject functor is representable.

First, suppose *\xrightarrow {\top }\Omega is a subobject classifier. We claim that \Omega represents \operatorname {Sub}_C. Indeed, the assignment (s\hookrightarrow x)\xmapsto {\chi } x\xrightarrow {\chi _s} \Omega of a subobject to its characteristic map is a natural bijection \operatorname {Sub}(x)\to C(x, \Omega ). To demonstrate bijectivity, note that pulling back \top along a map x\xrightarrow {\chi _0} \Omega yields a subobject of x with characteristic map \chi _0; this assignment is unique by uniqueness of pullbacks.

fr:mainmatter.fr:p: We dedicate this book to the memory of J. Frank Adams. His clear insights have inspired many mathematicians, including both of us. In January 1989, when the first draft of our book had been completed, we heard the sad news of his untimely death. This has cast a shadow on our subsequent work. Our views of topos theory, as presented here, have been shaped by continued study, by conferences, and by many personal contacts with friends and colleagues-including especially O. Bruno, P. Freyd, J.M.E. Hyland, P.T. Johnstone, A. Joyal, A. Kock, F.W. Lawvere, G.E. Reyes, R Solovay, R Swan, RW. Thomason, M. Tierney, and G.C. Wraith. Our presentation combines ideas and results from these people and from many others, but we have not endeavored to specify the various original sources. Moreover, a number of people have assisted in our work by pro viding helpful comments on portions of the manuscript. In this respect, we extend our hearty thanks in particular to P. Corazza, K. Edwards, J. Greenlees, G. Janelidze, G. Lewis, and S. Schanuel.

fr:title.text: Subobject classifiers are unique up to isomorphism

fr:frontmatter.fr:title: Subobject classifiers are unique up to isomorphism

fr:mainmatter.fr:p: Subobject classifiers are unique up to isomorphism.

fr:tree.fr:mainmatter: Subobject classifiers represent the subobject functor and representations are unique.

fr:mainmatter.fr:p: Dually, f is epic if and only if its cokernel pair is 1_y.

Suppose f is monic; then for any pair of maps z\overset {g, h}{\rightrightarrows } x such that fg = fh, g = h, so that g satisfies the universal property of the pullback; it is the only map which does so, again since f is monic.
Conversely, suppose the square is a pullback; then given maps z\xrightarrow {g, h} x such that fg = fh, both g and h witness the universal property, so uniqueness implies g = h.
The universal properties mutually imply each other by a diagam chase.
A category is finite if it has only finitely many morphisms.
A category C is locally small if for each pair of objects x and y, the collection C(x, y) forms a set.
A category is complete if it has all small limits.

fr:title.text: Limits are unique up to unique isomorphism

fr:frontmatter.fr:title: Limits are unique up to unique isomorphism

fr:mainmatter.fr:p: Limits are unique up to unique isomorphism of cones. Explicitly, let J\xrightarrow {d} C be a diagram and suppose x\xrightarrow {\lambda } D and y\xrightarrow {\mu } D are both limiting cones. Then there is a unique isomorphism x\to y commuting with the \lambda and \mu .
Dually, colimits are unique up to unique isomorphism of cocones.

This follows from the characterization of representable isomorphism, but we give a direct proof. To show isomorphism, note that the universal property of limits induces a pair of unique maps x\xtofrom [g]{f} y commuting with the cones; it remains to show these are isomorphisms. The composite gf is a map x\to x commuting with the cone \lambda , but 1_x is another such map, so by uniqueness of suchs maps gf = 1_x. The same works on the other side.
An terminal object is a limit of an empty diagram.
By the universal property of limits, an object t is terminal in the category C if and only if for every object c, there is a unique morphism c\to t.

A (covariant) functor C\xrightarrow {F} Set is representable if there exists an object c\in C and a natural isomorphism C(c, -)\cong F to the covariant hom-functor. A representation of F is a choice of such data.
Dually, a contravariant functor C^\text {op}\xrightarrow {F} Set is representable if there exists an object c\in C and a natural isomorphism C(-, c)\cong F to the contravariant hom-functor.

Let c be an object in a category C. The contravariant hom-functor C^\text {op}\xrightarrow {C(-, c)} Set takes an object x to the hom-set C(x, c) and a morphism x\xrightarrow {f} y to its action f^* by pre-composition:
This functor is also called the presheaf represented by c, and is written yc, y^c or h^c, the former two in reference to the Yoneda embedding.
A natural isomorphism is an isomorphism in a functor category. Explicitly, it is a natural transformation whose components are each isomorphisms.
